<h1>Rucking</h1>

<img class="image" src="/Images/Rucking.jpg">

<p>Rucking is key! They're an opportunity to tie-in defenders or even steal the ball. This is why rucking isn't just something that you have to do, but it's something that you should use to your advantage.</p>

<p>There are a lot of rules around rucking. Some rules are for safety, but most of them are to make it a fair contest for the ball.</p>

<p>You may spend a lot of time in training working on your scrummaging, kicking or lineout skills, but in the 2019 Rugby World Cup there were an average 129 tackles in a match and 82 rucks as result of them. This compares to 14 scrums and 25 lineouts. This is why it's so important to learn what to do in a ruck situation.</p>

<h3>Rucking as a defending player</h3>

<p>There are three decisions that you should make when you see an opposition player get tackled, in order they are:</p>
<ol>
    <li>Jackal.</li>
    <li>Counter-ruck.</li>
    <li>Let the opposition win it and join the defensive line.</li>
</ol>

<p>Let's go through these options and explain them...</p>

<h5>Jackaling</h5>

<p>A ruck is formed when at least one player from each team is bound over the ball. It's important to remember and understand that sentence because until a ruck is formed, none of the rules of the ruck apply.</p>

<p>In a ruck, you're not allowed to touch the ball with your hands. However, if you grabbed the ball before the ruck formed, then you don't have to take your hands off it. This is how you can steal the ball from a tackled player. It's called jackaling and successfully stealing possession in this way is almost as good as scoring.</p>

<p>An important rule to remember is that tacklers must release the player and ball before getting up and being allowed to jackal. To make it clear to the referee, you must briefly lift your hands up to show you are no longer part of the tackle. After you have completed all of this and a ruck has not been formed, you may jackal the ball.</p>

<p>Opposition players will try to push you off the ball, so you must stand in the "tower of power" position whilst jackaling. If you're not on your feet, you must release the ball. That includes when your knee or hand either touches the ground or touches another player who is on the ground.</p>

<p>If the tackled player doesn't let you steal the ball, then they could be penalised for holding-on while off their feet. Receiving a penalty is even better than just stealing possession.</p>

