<h5>Letting the oppostion win it</h5>

<p>This may sound counter-productive, but if you have players involved in a ruck that you're not going to win, then those players aren't in your defensive line. If you have 3 tacklers on the floor and 2 more players attempting to counter-ruck, then you only have 10 players left to form the D-line.</p>

<p>If you watch a professional rugby match, you'll see multiple phases where the defending players don't attempt to jackal or counter-ruck and they simply join the D-line to close the gaps and put in the next big hit.</p>

<h3>Rucking as an attacking player</h3>

<iframe class="video" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/HaSL73w_e8A" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>

<p>Take a look at the above video. These professional players are so quick at rucking. This is because it's easy for the opposition to steal the ball. They also do it quickly so that their D-line doesn't have a chance to re-organise themselves.</p>

<p>When one of your players is tackled, you must ensure 2 or 3 of your players stand, bound-together, over the ball to prevent the opposition from jackaling or counter-rucking. This is why it's useful to work in pods of 3 or 4 forwards when attacking.</p>

<p>If you're attacking near to the opposition's try-line, the forwards should consider a "pick and go" manoeuvre, where a forward will pick the ball up from the back of the ruck, rather than leaving it for the scrum half. Then 2 or 3 other forwards bind onto them and they attack the fringes of the ruck as a pod to force the ball carrier further forwards or over the try-line to score. A player would usually get smashed if they tried this on their own.</p>